  "fullDescription": "Ambrosia (Greek: ἀμβροσία, meaning \"immortal\" or \"not mortal\") is the divine food of the Olympian gods, conferring immortality and preserving eternal youth. Along with nectar, the divine drink, ambrosia sustained the gods and distinguished them fundamentally from mortals. This sacred substance appears throughout Greek mythology as both a literal food and a symbol of divine nature, the unbridgeable gap between gods and humans, and the tantalizing possibility of transcending mortal limits.\n\nThe word ambrosia derives from Greek roots:\n\nThus, ambrosia literally means \"that which is not mortal\" or \"immortal substance.\" The name itself embodies its essential function - to remove mortality and grant eternal life. This direct naming contrasts with the mystery surrounding similar substances in other traditions (like soma), making ambrosia's purpose explicit from its very designation.",
